Convert time columns to datetime

In[14]:
df['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['start_time'])
df['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['end_time'])

Derive new columns

In[15]:
df['duration_min'] = df['duration_sec'] / 60
df['hour'] = df['start_time'].dt.hour
df['day'] = df['start_time'].dt.day_name()
In[16]:
df['age'] = 2019 - df['member_birth_year']
In[17]:
df = df[(df['age'] >= 10) & (df['age'] <= 90)]

Functions

In[18]:
def hist_plot(data, col, bins=50, xlim=None, title='', xlabel='', ylabel='Count'):
    
    plt.figure()
    sns.histplot(data[col], bins=bins, kde=True)
    if xlim: plt.xlim(xlim)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()
    
def count_plot(data, col, title="", xlabel="", ylabel="count"):
    
    plt.figure()
    sns.countplot(x=col, data=data)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()
    
def box_plot(data, x, y, ylim=None, title='', xlabel='', ylabel=''):
    
    plt.figure()
    sns.boxplot(x=x, y=y, data=data)
    if ylim: plt.ylim(ylim)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()
    
def line_plot(df, x, y, title="", xlabel="", ylabel=""):
    
    plt.figure()
    sns.lineplot(x=x, y=y, data=df, marker="o")
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()    
    
def heat_map(df, rows, cols, values, title="", xlabel="", ylabel=""):
    
    pivot=df.pivot(index="day", columns="hour", values="count")
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.heatmap(pivot, cmap='YlGnBu')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?

The main variable of interest, trip duration, is right skewed, meaning that most rides are short in duration, typically under 30 minutes, while a small number of trips last much longer. These long trips represent outliers but are still plausible. To improve interpretability, the duration was converted from seconds to minutes. The histogram clearly shows a concentration of trips between 520 minutes, with a gradual decline afterward.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Some categorical variables such as gender and user_type showed imbalanced distributions males and subscribers dominate the dataset. Missing values were found in several columns (like member_birth_year and member_gender) and were removed to maintain data integrity. Additionally, new features were derived for deeper exploration:

duration_min (converted from seconds)

hour and day (from start_time)

age (calculated as 2019 member_birth_year) These transformations helped in visualizing temporal and demographic patterns more clearly.

In[24]:
# Heatmap of trip counts by day and hour
trips_heat = df.groupby(['day','hour']).size().reset_index(name='count')
ordered_days = ['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday']
trips_heat['day'] = pd.Categorical(trips_heat['day'], categories=ordered_days, ordered=True)
heat_map(trips_heat, 'day', 'hour', 'count',
         title='Trips by Day and Hour', xlabel='Hour of Day', ylabel='Day of Week')

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

When examining trip duration by user type, subscribers take more rides but for shorter periods, while customers take fewer but longer trips likely due to leisure usage. When comparing trip duration by gender, females and other genders tend to have slightly longer trip durations than males on average. Analyzing the relationship between trip duration and time of day, the average duration remains relatively consistent throughout the day, with slight increases during midday hours.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Yes. The heatmap of trip counts by hour and day of week revealed strong commuting patterns: peak activity around 8 AM and 5 PM during weekdays. This suggests that the majority of rides are for commuting purposes rather than recreation. Additionally, the user type and gender relationship shows that male subscribers represent the largest segment, indicating a demographic bias in the user base.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

Combining trip duration, hour, and gender revealed that females tend to take slightly longer trips across most hours of the day. The relationship between age and duration also supported this finding younger riders (especially those aged 2035) are more active and tend to ride longer. These variables together reinforced the idea that demographic and temporal factors both influence ride behavior.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

An interesting interaction appeared between day of week, hour, and user type:

Subscribers mainly ride during weekdays and commute hours, showing consistent peaks.

Customers, on the other hand, ride more during weekends and outside of rush hours, indicating leisure-oriented patterns.

This interaction highlights how time-based and demographic features combine to explain the distinct behaviors between user segments

Conclusions

Summary of Findings:

  • Most trips are short, under 30 minutes.
  • Subscribers take significantly more trips than customers.
  • Male members are the majority of riders.
  • Trip duration tends to be slightly longer for customers than subscribers.
  • Most rides occur during morning and evening commute hours (8 AM, 5 PM).
  • Weekdays show higher usage patterns than weekends.
  • Younger riders tend to take longer trips on average.
